{"candidates":[{"content":"{\"claim\": \"Harness criticism strictly beats self-consistency only when candidate base error exceeds 50% so that self-consistency's majority is wrong, while critic recall on the wrong majority exceeds (1 - precision) times the fraction of correct-majority questions the critic will false-flag.\",\"mechanism\": \"Self-consistency computes the mode of k candidates; when base error > 0.5 the mode is the wrong answer. The critic acts as a binary classifier over candidate sets; it can add value only by vetoing the wrong majority while sparing the right one. Net benefit = recall_wrong * p_wrong_majority - FPR_right * p_right_majority, where FPR_right = 1 - precision on right-majority sets. Thus filtering strictly improves aggregate accuracy only in the intermediate regime: p_wrong_majority large enough and critic selectivity high enough that the first term dominates the second. The repository's measured null results (v4-pro hard: p_right_majority ~1, recall 1, precision 0.125) are the special case where there is nothing to fix and false flags are harmless only because the base majority was already right; at slightly higher base error the same precision would erode correct majorities and cause net loss.\",\"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"intermediate base error 0.35-0.65\", \"critic recall on wrong-majority sets >= 0.5\", \"critic precision >= 0.5\", \"k=5 or k=7\"], \"excludes\": [\"base error < 0.2 (majority already right, filtering can only hurt)\", \"base error > 0.8 (majority robustly wrong, critic recall unlikely to rescue)\", \"perfect or near-perfect critic precision with near-zero recall\"]},\"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Experiment arm with base error 0.40-0.55 and critic precision >= 0.5 and recall >= 0.5 shows harness accuracy <= self-consistency accuracy on >= 60% of questions in that regime\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"Experiment arm with base error 0.40-0.55 and critic precision < 0.5 shows harness accuracy >= self-consistency accuracy on >= 50% of questions\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"Across all intermediate-base-error arms, the measured quantity recall_wrong * p_wrong_majority - FPR_right * p_right_majority is negative while harness accuracy exceeds self-consistency\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}],\"prose_notes\": \"The decisive experiment: construct ~120 questions across five base-error bins (0.15, 0.30, 0.45, 0.60, 0.75) by mixing difficulty tiers and prompting noise; generate k=5 candidates per question with one shared pool; run critic filter and raw majority vote; record per-question majority correctness, critic verdict, critic precision/recall stratified by whether the majority was right or wrong; compute net-fixed-minus-broke per bin. Expected signature: harness strictly beats SC in the 0.45-0.60 bin when critic precision >= 0.5, and harness loses to SC in the 0.15-0.30 bin when critic precision < 0.4 because false flags erode already-correct majorities. Token budget: 120 q * 5 cand * ~800 tokens generation + 120 q * ~600 tokens critic + ~3000 tokens analysis ~= 147k tokens, within 300k.\"}","refs":[{"role":"dependence","target":"495c5963dafbd26bf2aa1838491e8428005b9a54825f21a8df1e5ead37908e7a"},{"role":"dependence","target":"ba687c5f145e404c53a84549cf366e0b6e0106eec67404c07231357fed09e672"}],"typicality":0.92},{"content":"{\"claim\": \"Harness criticism's strict advantage over self-consistency emerges primarily at odd k >= 7 when the wrong-answer concentration is thin (a bare 4-of-7 majority) and the critic possesses high precision on exactly those bare-majority wrong sets, because self-consistency's tie-breaking resolves noise while the critic removes a structurally identifiable wrong cluster.\",\"mechanism\": \"At k=5 the majority margin is at least 3-vs-2, giving self-consistency a weak but decisive signal; when the pool is already right 4-of-5 (as in the repository's hard set) filtering is redundant and when it is wrong 3-of-2 the critic has too little signal to distinguish a wrong majority from a right one with the observed precision 0.125. Increasing k to 7 creates a richer margin structure: bare 4-of-7 wrong majorities carry distinctive candidate-set features (near-tie entropy, higher variance in reasoning quality among the 4) that a critic can learn to flag at higher precision than the blunt k=5 case. The critic thus converts close-call noise that self-consistency would lock in as a wrong mode into a rerun or abstention, strictly improving accuracy when bare-majority wrong sets are common (base error ~0.55-0.65) and critic precision on bare-majority sets exceeds ~0.7.\",\"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"k=7 or k=9\", \"base error 0.50-0.70 (thin wrong majorities)\", \"critic precision on bare-majority wrong sets >= 0.7\"], \"excludes\": [\"k=5 (margin structure too coarse)\", \"base error < 0.40 (robust right majorities)\", \"base error > 0.75 (robust wrong majorities, critic cannot rescue even at high precision)\"]},\"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"At k=7 with base error 0.55-0.65 and critic precision on bare-majority wrong sets >= 0.7, harness accuracy is not strictly greater than self-consistency on >= 60% of questions in that bin\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"At k=7 with base error 0.55-0.65, critic precision on bare-majority wrong sets < 0.4, and harness accuracy still exceeds self-consistency on >= 50% of questions\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"The improvement at k=7 is fully explained by base-error change alone with no interaction effect from critic precision on bare-majority sets\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}],\"prose_notes\": \"Experiment: 100 questions at base error ~0.60, generate pools at k=5, k=7, k=9 (same questions, same seeds, just more samples); compute per-k self-consistency accuracy and harness accuracy; measure critic precision/recall stratified by margin (bare-majority vs robust-majority). Test for interaction: harness-SC gap should grow with k only when critic precision on bare-majority wrong sets is high. Token budget: 100 q * 9 cand * 800 tokens + 100 q * 3 critic runs * 600 tokens + analysis ~= 120k.\"}","refs":[{"role":"dependence","target":"495c5963dafbd26bf2aa1838491e8428005b9a54825f21a8df1e5ead37908e7a"},{"role":"dependence","target":"74fde5320d6c79520ea82d22a3e0c25a5ecc8e0cb50c3197058c5a3b0ecd2845"}],"typicality":0.55},{"content":"{\"claim\": \"No fixed precision/recall regime suffices; harness strictly beats self-consistency only when critic confidence is question-adaptive such that the critic vetoes wrong-majority sets at high confidence and abstains on right-majority sets, making the effective per-question FPR near zero while maintaining nonzero recall on wrong sets.\",\"mechanism\": \"The repository's data show that a single global critic decision (veto/allow) with fixed precision 0.125 and recall 1.0 yields zero net benefit because the critic flags everything, so filtering is a no-op on the already-correct majority. The causal failure is not the critic's recall but its inability to discriminate which veto signals are reliable. If instead the critic outputs a calibrated confidence p_veto and the harness vetoes only when p_veto > threshold tau, then at high tau the critic abstains on most right-majority questions (FPR -> 0) while still catching wrong-majority questions where the evidence is strong. The strict advantage regime is therefore not a point in (base error, precision, recall, k) space but a curve: for any base error in (0.5-p, 0.5+p) where p scales with 1/sqrt(k), there exists a threshold tau making the expected net-fixed-minus-broke positive if and only if the critic's score distribution for wrong-majority sets stochastically dominates its score distribution for right-majority sets.\",\"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"critic outputs calibrated confidence, not binary veto\", \"thresholded veto policy with tunable tau\", \"base error 0.40-0.70\", \"any k >= 5\"], \"excludes\": [\"binary veto critic with fixed global precision/recall\", \"critic score distributions for right and wrong majorities are identical\"]},\"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Critic score distributions for right-majority and wrong-majority sets are indistinguishable (KS test p > 0.05) yet thresholded harness strictly beats self-consistency on >= 50% of questions\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"Critic score distributions are separable (KS p < 0.05) but no threshold tau yields positive net-fixed-minus-broke averaged over the test set\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"The optimal-threshold harness accuracy exceeds self-consistency but the binary-veto harness accuracy also exceeds self-consistency by the same margin, contradicting that adaptivity is necessary\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}],\"prose_notes\": \"Experiment: reuse the repository's 44 questions plus 60 new questions spanning base error 0.30-0.70; generate k=5 candidates; instead of binary critic veto, prompt the critic to output a confidence score 0-1 for 'this candidate set's majority is wrong'; sweep tau in {0.5, 0.7, 0.8, 0.9, 0.95}; compute per-tau harness accuracy and net-fixed-minus-broke; also run the binary-veto harness for comparison. Confirm: (1) at high tau, FPR on right-majority sets drops below 0.1 while recall on wrong-majority sets stays above 0.3; (2) there exists tau where harness strictly beats SC; (3) binary veto does not match this. Token budget: 104 q * 5 cand * 800 tokens + 104 q * 600 critic + 104 q * 5 thresholds * 50 eval + analysis ~= 86k.\"}","refs":[{"role":"dependence","target":"495c5963dafbd26bf2aa1838491e8428005b9a54825f21a8df1e5ead37908e7a"},{"role":"dependence","target":"ba687c5f145e404c53a84549cf366e0b6e0106eec67404c07231357fed09e672"}],"typicality":0.25}]}